---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="AuDHD and Burnout: Why You're Not Just Tired"
  description="AuDHD burnout goes beyond exhaustion. Understand the causes, warning signs, recovery strategies, and how to prevent it from happening again."
  type="article"
>
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-12">
    <header class="mb-10">
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-text">AuDHD and Burnout</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-text-light leading-relaxed">
        Regular burnout is running a marathon and hitting the wall at mile 20. AuDHD burnout is running that marathon while also translating a foreign language, processing a rock concert's worth of sensory input, and pretending you enjoy all of it. For years. Without a break. Here's what that does to a person, and how to come back from it.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="space-y-8">
      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">What Makes AuDHD Burnout Different</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Standard burnout advice tells you to take a vacation, get more sleep, practice self-care. AuDHD burnout doesn't respond to a spa day. It's not about working too hard (though that's often part of it). It's about the cumulative cost of operating in a world that wasn't designed for your neurology. Masking, sensory processing, executive function compensation, social translation. These run in the background constantly, draining resources that nobody sees you spending.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          <strong class="text-text">Autistic burnout</strong> typically comes from sustained masking and sensory overload. It can reduce your functioning across the board: skills you've had for years suddenly become difficult. <strong class="text-text">ADHD burnout</strong> comes from chronic understimulation or overstimulation, inconsistent energy, and the exhaustion of compensating for executive function gaps. In AuDHD, both types hit simultaneously, and they feed each other in a cycle that's difficult to break without understanding what's driving it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">The Causes</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Burnout rarely comes from one thing. It's an accumulation that eventually overwhelms your capacity to compensate. Common contributors for AuDHD people include:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-text-light leading-relaxed list-disc pl-6">
          <li><strong class="text-text">Chronic masking.</strong> Performing neurotypicality for 8+ hours at work, then coming home with nothing left. Over months and years, this creates a deficit that weekends can't fix.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Sensory environments you can't control.</strong> Open-plan offices, fluorescent lighting, shared living spaces with constant noise. Your nervous system is working overtime just to tolerate the baseline.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Life transitions.</strong> New jobs, moves, relationship changes, having children. <a href="/blog/audhd-and-parenting/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">Parenting</a> is a particularly common burnout trigger because it combines every stressor at once.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Inadequate recovery time.</strong> Your brain needs more downtime than a neurotypical brain. Not because you're weak, but because you're processing more. If your schedule doesn't account for this, burnout is a matter of when, not if.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Late diagnosis or no diagnosis.</strong> Not knowing you're AuDHD means not knowing why you need accommodations, which means you push through without them until you can't anymore.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Warning Signs to Watch For</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          AuDHD burnout usually builds gradually, which makes it easy to miss until you're deep in it. Early signs often get dismissed as laziness, depression, or "just a bad week."
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          <strong class="text-text">Loss of skills</strong> is the hallmark sign. Things you could do before become genuinely difficult. Cooking meals you've made a hundred times feels impossible. Phone calls that were manageable become terrifying. Executive function, already compromised, drops further. You might lose words mid-sentence or forget how to do routine tasks at work.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Other signs include increased sensory sensitivity (sounds that were tolerable now feel painful), withdrawal from social interaction (even from people you love), emotional flatness or sudden outbursts, increased meltdowns or shutdowns, and physical symptoms like chronic fatigue, headaches, or getting sick more often. Your <a href="/learn/signs-of-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">usual AuDHD traits</a> intensify. Stimming increases. Masking becomes nearly impossible.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          If this sounds like your current state, our <a href="/quiz/audhd-burnout/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">AuDHD burnout quiz</a> can help you assess where you are.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Recovery Takes Longer Than You Think</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Here's what nobody tells you: AuDHD burnout recovery is measured in months, sometimes years. Not weeks. The depth of depletion is proportional to how long you were running on empty before you recognized what was happening. A weekend off won't touch it. A week's vacation helps, but you'll likely crash again within days of returning to the same environment.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Real recovery requires changing the conditions that caused the burnout, not just resting within the same conditions and going back:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-text-light leading-relaxed list-disc pl-6">
          <li><strong class="text-text">Reduce masking demands.</strong> This might mean disclosing at work, changing jobs, or restructuring your social life. Hard conversations, but necessary ones.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Modify your sensory environment.</strong> Work from home if possible. Control lighting. Use ear protection. Remove sensory stressors that you've been "tolerating" at a cost you couldn't see.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Drop the standards.</strong> Not permanently, but during recovery, "good enough" replaces "doing it right." Frozen meals. Messy house. Cancelled plans. This isn't failure. This is triage.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-text">Build recovery into your schedule permanently.</strong> Not as a reward, but as infrastructure. Regular downtime isn't optional for an AuDHD brain. It's maintenance.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Prevention (Because You Don't Want to Do This Twice)</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Once you've recovered, the instinct is to jump back to full capacity. Resist that. The goal is to build a sustainable baseline that your nervous system can maintain long-term, not return to the conditions that burned you out in the first place.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Prevention looks like: knowing your limits (not your "push through it" limits, your actual limits), having early warning indicators you check regularly, building buffer into your schedule for bad days, and giving yourself permission to need what you need without justifying it. A life that requires constant masking and compensation will always lead back to burnout. The structural changes are where the real prevention lives.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          If you suspect burnout is part of your story and you haven't been assessed for AuDHD yet, understanding your neurology is the first step toward building something sustainable. Our <a href="/quiz/is-it-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">AuDHD quiz</a> can help clarify the picture, and the <a href="/learn/getting-assessed/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">assessment guide</a> covers what to do from there.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 bg-accent/10 rounded-[--radius-xl] p-6 sm:p-8">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-text mb-3">Explore More</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2">
        <li><a href="/quiz/audhd-burnout/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">Take the Burnout Quiz &rarr;</a></li>
        <li><a href="/quiz/is-it-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">Take the AuDHD Quiz &rarr;</a></li>
        <li><a href="/blog/late-diagnosis-audhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">Late diagnosis: grief, relief, and identity &rarr;</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
